<TEXT>
here is a chronology of events in the case 
of byron de la beckwith arrested in tennessee after being indicted 
again in the 1963 assassination of civil rights leader medgar 
evers 
june 12 1963 evers the mississippi naacp field secretary is 
shot in the back outside his home 
june 21 1963 beckwith is arrested by the fbi on a civil 
rights complaint authorities say his fingerprint was found on the 
telescopic sight of a rifle found near the scene beckwith claims 
the rifle was stolen from his home 
jan 27 1964 beckwiths first state trial on a murder charge 
begins with an allwhite jury the trial ends in a hung jury on 
feb 7 
april 6 1964 beckwiths second trial begins again with an 
allwhite jury jurors report they are deadlocked on april 17 
1969 the murder charge against beckwith is dismissed 
1973 beckwith is arrested in new orleans and convicted of 
possessing dynamite without a permit he served five years in 
prison 
october 1989 published reports say the mississippi sovereignty 
commission a nowdefunct state segregationist watchdog agency 
screened potential jurors in beckwiths second trial prosecutors 
later announce they found no evidence of jury tampering 
oct 3 1989 evers widow myrlie asks that her husbands 
murder case be reopened jackson city council naacp and others 
support reopening the case 
march 11 1990 district attorney ed peters announces there are 
new leads in the evers case 
dec 17 1990 beckwith is arrested in tennessee on a fugitive 
warrant issued by the state of mississippi 
</TEXT>
