<TEXT>
some scrooges say its those little red and green things 
that make them think youd have to be nuttier than a fruitcake to 
eat one others drag out the joke you know the one about there 
being just one fruitcake that gets passed around and around and 
around 
its the only thing that everybody doesnt like except 
lutefisk the humorist calvin trillin says referring to a 
norwegian dried cod dish 
but have you ever eaten fruitcake mr trillin 
i think i had a bite once 20 years ago it was before i knew 
i was an innocent he says probably it was christmas the fire 
was going the presents were being unwrapped or maybe they already 
were unwrapped 
fruitcake has had its share of humiliation johnny carson and 
columnist russell baker have poked fun nearly a third of the 
people surveyed by american express a couple of years back said it 
was the worst gift of all 
well mr trillin mr baker and all you other naysayers enough 
already 
its sort of an annual plague said susan purdy author of 
the cookbook a piece of cake who argues theres more to 
fruitcake than men of this ilk know 
im not going to sit here and tell you that when you hear a 
fruitcake joke it doesnt make you kind of mad it does said w 
dale parker a vice president at the granddaddy of fruitcake 
bakers claxton bakery inc in claxton ga 
parkers family business bakes 5 million pounds of fruitcake a 
year 
obviously theres a lot of people out there eating 
fruitcake parker said 
we get some rave reviews that its just like the one 
grandmother wanted to bake but couldnt boasts father andrew of 
the holy cross abbey in berryville va where each year the 
monastery bakery turns out 13000 traditional fruit and 
nutstudded cakes laced with brandy 
so mr trillin how do you suppose these companies stay in 
business 
people are buying them and theyre giving them to other 
people but that doesnt mean theyre eating them he said 
ive been given a lot of fruitcakes as gifts 
richard sullivan of the glace fruit processors admits some 
fruitcakes taste like sawdust his father always got one for 
christmas that was dense and bitter i never liked the thing 
ah but then there are good ones 
they have to have wonderful fruits said purdy who uses 
mangoes papayas apricots dates nuts dried apples pears and 
plums she advises avoid little red and green and yellow 
things 
a good fruitcake to me is like eating candy sullivan said 
i just love it 
melvin gordon president of paradise fruit inc in plant city 
fla said he doesnt know how fruitcake got such a lousy 
reputation 
he notes that his industry sells 50 million pounds of candied 
fruit a year and if he could talk to mr trillin hed say 
fruitcake has been around a lot longer than you and i 
even some particular fruitcakes can claim that 
in enoughs enough a new collection of trillins columns 
he mentions a family in michigan that brings out an antique 
fruitcake every christmas a fruitcake that for some reason was not 
eaten at christmas dinner in 1895 and has symbolized the holidays 
ever since 
mr trillin meet morgan ford of tecumseh mich keeper of a 
cake baked not in 1895 he says but in 1878 by his 
greatgrandmother 
when she died early the following year the cake was forgotten 
for a while today its in an airtight glass box ford said 
theres a musty rum smell there yet he said 
when his uncle then 86 took a bite a couple decades back ford 
said he had to cut it off with his jacknife sliver it off it 
doesnt look too appetizing to me 
as if to ward off the inevitable ford notes right away that his 
uncle lived two more years 
if i make it to 86 and im 70 ill taste it then he 
said 
but he could be persuaded to give into temptation by johnny 
carson who has poked fun at the cake if hed take a bite 
ford said id take a bite 
go ahead mr trillin joke about heirloom or antique 
fruitcakes age can be a virtue 
the late james beard often called the dean of american food 
once wrote that his mother baked fruitcakes a full year ahead and 
kept some of her wedding fruitcake for a quartercentury by 
periodically lacing it with cognac 
the ancient romans purdy said baked fruitcakes called 
satura latin for a full dish and the root of the word 
satire perhaps the romans had one up on you mr trillin 
martha washington made one for family holidays before 
refrigeration the sugar and spirits in fruitcakes acted as 
preservatives 
as recently as 50 years ago no one chortled over fruitcake 
our taste has changed we dont like things that are too 
heavy too sweet purdy said were talking about an antique 
cake in contemporary life and its trying to make the 
transition 
so go ahead take your potshots mr trillin and co but 
honestly wouldnt you be in a holiday funk if nobody at all 
remembered you with a fruitcake 
 
editors note mary macvean comes from a long line of fruitcake 
lovers and nevers lets a december go by without eating or baking 
some with or without the little red and green fruit 
</TEXT>
