<TEXT>
lawrence e walsh ends his fourth year as 
irancontra prosecutor today fighting to preserve his most 
important convictions and pry evidence from unwilling witnesses to 
complete his investigation 
congress and much of the public appear to have forgotten or at 
least lost interest in the biggest scandal of the reagan 
administration 
but a grand jury continues to hear evidence in the case and 
walsh says he will decide by spring whether to seek new indictments 
or conclude his investigation 
in the meantime walsh gets a chilly reception from the bush 
administration whose hardline stance on releasing classified 
documents scuttled the prosecution of former cia agent joseph 
fernandez 
he endures the editorial taunts of conservative commentators 
one recently compared him to a dinner guest who wont go home 
his office is still dueling in closed court proceedings with 
oliver l north over the former white house aides refusal to give 
more testimony to the grand jury 
north scored a major victory earlier this year when a federal 
appeals court set aside his three felony convictions for his role 
in covering up the sale of us arms to iran and the diversion of 
profits to the nicaraguan contra rebels 
the decision bodes ill for walshs other major triumph five 
guilty verdicts earlier this year against former national security 
adviser john m poindexter convicted of lying to congress and 
obstructing its investigations 
poindexters appeal is set to be argued feb 28 
and now walsh is fighting a rearguard action against jeffrey 
toobin a former junior associate of his office who wants to 
publish a book about the irancontra investigation that the 
independent counsel contends would expose grand jury secrets 
toobin has filed suit against walsh in new york 
i have never felt in the center of friends said walsh a 
former federal judge and wall street lawyer who is a month shy of 
his 79th birthday but looks at least 10 years younger this has 
always been a lonely place 
but walsh who shuttles between washington and his home in 
oklahoma city said his investigation achieved its goal of 
uncovering the wrongs of the irancontra affair 
the central actors have been pretty well described he said 
in an interview while acknowledging that the supervisory and 
support roles may never be fully exposed 
when the investigation is over we will have substantially a 
full story but there will undoubtedly be enclaves that arent 
fully developed walsh said 
eight participants have been convicted including poindexter 
north former national security adviser robert mcfarlane and arms 
dealers richard v secord and albert hakim 
just last week thomas g clines received a 16month sentence 
the longest prison term imposed on an irancontra defendant for 
failing to report on his tax returns all the money he earned 
brokering the arms deals 
the grand jury is trying to determine whether other former 
reagan administration officials could be prosecuted for misleading 
congress about the covert operation to arm the nicaraguan rebels 
these former officials include elliott abrams a former 
assistant secretary of state and donald gregg an adviser to 
thenvice president bush and now ambassador to south korea said 
sources familiar with the case who demanded anonymity 
walsh refused to comment on any aspect of the grand jury 
investigation 
he is preparing to ask the supreme court to revive norths 
convictions the appeals court had ruled that televised testimony 
north gave lawmakers under a congressional grant of immunity may 
have unfairly seeped into his trial 
that ruling gives poindexter powerful legal ammunition for his 
appeal 
like his former subordinate at the national security council 
poindexter gave congressional testimony on condition that his words 
would not be used as evidence against him 
walshdeclined to comment on the wisdom of the congressional 
grants of immunity but he acknowledged they posed a major 
stumbling block for his investigation 
the irancontra affair is most often compared to the watergate 
scandal that forced president nixons resignation 
but walsh said there are important differences that pose 
different problems for his investigation 
this isnt watergate where you have a burglary and a simple 
coverup this is a very complex operation at the very highest 
levels of government he said 
unlike the investigation by the watergate special prosecutor 
walshs probe has never definitively answered the question of the 
presidents role in the scandal 
but walsh said the irancontra investigations produced an 
unprecedented collection of ronald reagans statements 
particularly a sevenhour videotaped deposition the former 
president gave for poindexters trial 
its rare the public has been given his own view rather than 
the secondhand view of the investigator walsh said we have 
given the public the raw facts 
