government safety investigators say little can 
be done to force ship captains to rest even as they ruled acute 
fatigue a primary cause of rhode islands worst oil spill 
the national transportation safety board said monday that the 
captain of the greek tanker world prodigy had been on the bridge 35 
consecutive hours when the ship ran aground off newport ri on 
june 23 1989 
but the agency said there is little the government can do to 
force ship captains of foreignflag vessels to rest before reaching 
a us port 
hopefully what we can do is attenuate foreign ship operators 
that fatigue is a major hazard to transportation safety said 
ntsb chairman james l kolstad we see it in all modes of 
transportation clearly we saw it in this particular accident 
the board unanimously approved a report detailing how acute 
fatigue led capt iakovos georgoudis to make a series of dubious 
orders and miscalculations in the hours leading up to the 
grounding 
the spill of 289000 gallons of no 2 heating oil sent ribbons 
of pollution toward the rhode island coast in slicks as long as 
five miles shell fishing swimming and pleasure boating were 
halted in some areas 
the ntsb ruled out intoxication drug use or crew incompetence 
as possible causes 
board staffers described georgoudis as wellorganized and 
conscientious but said his sense of duty led him to overwork 
georgoudis told investigators he took several short naps on the 
bridge but remained there because he was worried about the weather 
and heavy ship traffic 
he had sent subordinates off the bridge to perform routine tasks 
and was himself distracted with cargo calculations as the ship 
approached the shallow water of brenton reef off newport ri 
georgoudis was off by more than a halfhour in his estimate of 
when the tanker would arrive at its rendezvous point with a boat 
carrying the harbor pilot and also made a slight but crucial course 
miscalculation that sent the ship on the wrong side of a warning 
buoy officials said 
the ntsb said the rhode island state pilotage commission 
contributed to the spill by failing to require that harbor pilots 
notify inbound vessels of exactly where they plan to board ship and 
guide it into port had that been done the board said the tanker 
would have waited to take on an experienced local pilot before 
proceeding through the reef area 
vernon dunlap chairman of the pilotage commission disputed the 
ntsb conclusion 
the vessels are always told that the pilot will board 
dunlap said the problem here was that the vessel arrived 45 
minutes early georgoudis arrived at the pilot boarding station 
and continued right across it 
