system is improved official sources said monday 
instead the report recommends giving the soviets help in 
carrying out fundamental economic reforms said the sources who 
spoke on condition of anonymity 
the study conducted by the international monetary fund world 
bank and two europeanbased development groups comes on the heels 
of a weekend summit at which western leaders ordered 1 billion in 
emergency aid for the soviets and approved spending more than that 
amount on technical assistance during the next two years 
last week bush promised a 13 billion loan guarantee package 
including up to 1 billion to buy us farm products and up to 300 
million to purchase us manufactured goods 
the soviets have been scrupulous about repaying their debts 
commerce secretary robert mosbacher said last week 
of course wed be liable if they default barbara clay a 
press officer at the us treasury said monday 
under the program outlined by bush the soviets would borrow 
from commercial banks to buy the food and manufactured goods the 
us government contribution will consist of a guarantee for those 
loans if the soviets fail to repay in three years the united 
states would pay the banks 98 percent of the principal and about 
half the interest 
in addition the us agency for international development will 
coordinate medical aid to be provided by private organizations the 
agency may help pay the private groups administrative costs aid 
spokesman john riddle said 
the soviets have paid cash for billions of dollars worth of 
grain and other food bought from this country 
the commodity credit corporation the us agency that 
guarantees the loans for food purchases said that without a 
government guarantee the soviets might not be able to get the loans 
at all 
nobody wants to make a threeyear loan on something thats 
going to be eaten up in a few weeks explained deputy director 
robert s simpson 
the loan guarantees for manufactured goods will be offered 
through the governments exportimport bank the bank has not lent 
to the soviets since 1975 
bank spokeswoman ann frye said the loan guarantee would 
encourage commercial banks to give the soviet union better terms 
than it might otherwise get including a break of up to 1 percent 
on the interest rate 
the studys findings according to the official sources were 
pessimistic and depressing because they describe a system even more 
backward than expected and practically paralyzed by inefficiency 
and confusion 
no amount of aid will make a real difference the system 
simply cannot absorb it the pipe is so porous that very little 
would reach its intended target said ilya prizel of the johns 
hopkins school for advanced international studies 
prizel said a political statement in the form of food aid to 
help soviets get through the winter might shore up president 
mikhail s gorbachev or even help induce the kinds of reform that 
are necessary 
but prizel said what they need is technical assistance 
everything from entrepreneurial and managerial assistance to 
logistical assistance as well as traditional advice such as how 
to set up a central bank 
the soviet currency the ruble is not traded on international 
exchanges and its value inside the country is in a free fall the 
price of goods bears little or no relationship to the cost of 
production inflation is accelerating at a pace difficult to 
measure and manufacturing plants are almost universally old 
inefficient and unable to compete in world markets 
