<TEXT>
stalinist albania seems to have taken a 
giant step by permitting its first noncommunist party but many 
emigres and others are skeptical the change is genuine or 
sufficient to contain popular anger 
caught between a reluctance to relinquish a 46year monopoly on 
power and a desire to avoid mass violence the communist leadership 
has sent a series of contradictory signals in the past week 
president ramiz alia who a month ago denied any need for 
competing political parties has now pledged that reform is 
irreversible 
yet his government has to date kept all but a handful of foreign 
journalists from reporting independently on the historic events in 
his land it has also so far failed to accord the new democratic 
party of albania legality 
appeals from the new party for calm appeared in official media 
during last weeks riots in four cities but media have not carried 
details of its program or profiles of its leaders 
this puts the founders of the new party in a state of suspended 
animation working furiously on a program yet under pressure not 
to antagonize authorities apparently willing to take reform 
seriously 
the founders caution has also bred suspicion 
we dont know who these people running the new party are 
said an albanian intellectual who recently fled to greece and spoke 
on condition his name not be used 
he noted that economist gramoz pashko who has close ties to the 
communist elite helped found the new party 
just as in romania and bulgaria the governing party is 
pretending to put on a new face to subvert opposition to it the 
people rioting on the streets are the real opposition to the 
regime 
in a country of 32 million people run for decades by a small 
secretive elite intellectuals have automatically enjoyed both 
privilege and close ties with the leadership 
yet they are among the few groups with the courage and power to 
organize in a country in which critics traditionally faced death or 
jail and the mystery that surrounds so much of what happens in 
totalitarian countries means these intellectuals cannot be sure who 
was involved in last weeks violence 
some echoed official language talking of dark forces and 
hinting that what one called some kind of new dictator was 
behind last weeks riots in shkodra elbasan durres and kavaje 
ismail kadare the renowned albanian author who defected to 
paris in october saying he despaired of seeing genuine democracy in 
albania told the french newspaper le figaro last week i fear a 
counterattack by conservative albanian forces 
if there is a power struggle between oldtime stalinists and 
reformers in the ruling albanian labor party last weeks violence 
could have been provoked by the conservatives 
yet popular discontent at economic misery and decades of 
repression is so high that the protests likely were spontaneous 
outbursts particularly in industrial centers like elbasan a city 
of 80000 in central albania with a huge steel mill employing some 
15000 workers 
elsewhere in the balkans similar mystery surrounds much of 
politics to this day for instance debate rages in romania over 
last years ouster of nicolae ceausescu 
was it in fact engineered by disillusioned communists and the 
military riding a wave of popular protest to seize control 
themselves or was it the true result of a popular uprising 
even the legitimacy conferred by election victories on the 
excommunists who took over in romania and bulgaria this year has 
proved insufficient for them to forge the consensus needed for the 
harsh economic reforms they recognize as inevitable 
romanias president ion iliescu opened negotiations monday on 
getting some opposition parties into the government 
a coalition government is to take office in bulgaria after 
strikes and economic chaos forced the socialist government to 
resign 
albanias elections scheduled for feb 10 will be a test of 
the communist partys willingness to accept democracy 
again this puts the new party in an awkward position in a 
backward country with poor communications and limited resources all 
controlled by the communists the democratic party faces an unequal 
contest in february 
pashko said monday that the new party has therefore asked for a 
postponement of the elections but that carries the risk of popular 
anger rising beyond anyones control 
the reforms need to be realized in a short time said nedim 
vlora an italian professor of albanian origin at bari university 
the situation is desperate and when a population is 
desperate it attacks it is essential that there be both economic 
and political reforms 
burhan kalaya who fled albania for italy three months ago said 
relatives reached by telephone in the albanian capital of tirana 
paint a confusing picture of optimism about change and despair 
at food shortages and other hardships 
such confusion prompts calls for the clear commitment to change 
that albania certainly must make if it is to meet the human rights 
standards of the conference on security and cooperation in europe 
it says it wants to join 
if they want us to believe in their claims of change let them 
allow christmas to be celebrated in religious ceremonies said a 
