<TEXT>
a childs shoe peeling away from its 
2inchhigh wooden sole an abdominal truss metal leg braces and 
plaster body parts all hang in a small shrine here 
i can remember when i was real small they had all the 
crutches the braces all around the altar tacked up there said 
albert hattier 61 
they are offerings of thanks to st roch who cared for victims 
of the black plague in the 1300s and himself survived the disease 
the faithful left them at the national shrine of st roch built in 
1875 after a yellow fever epidemic 
the items include models of healed organs and braces and 
crutches left by people who no longer needed them 
similar offerings are found in a number of european churches in 
a practice that dates at least to the middle ages 
these devotional offerings are a particularly latin 
expression said the rev john p ford a historian at catholic 
university in washington other people will give a window or 
a pew or a pulpit or candlesticks 
catholic churches in many us cities with large hispanic 
congregations have special rooms for such milagros said 
leonardo r anguiano a staff member at the mexicanamerican 
cultural center in san antonio texas 
most often he said they are tiny silver replicas of arms 
legs heads or other body parts sometimes they leave crutches 
sometimes they give thanks with a wedding dress sometimes with 
little baptismal outfits he said 
those at the shrine of st roch situated in a poor and 
workingclass neighborhood a few blocks outside the french quarter 
were moved from the altar in the 1950s during renovation to a tiny 
room next to the chapel 
the room is paved with marble tiles most inscribed thanks 
or merci a few tiles show the cured part a hand a leg a 
stomach 
thanks to st roch for my eye reads the inscription on one 
there is a 4foot statue of st lucy patron of people with eye 
troubles in her traditional pose a quill pen in her right hand 
and a pair of eyeballs anatomically correct down to the optic 
nerves on a plate in her left hand 
