impoverished masses a savior come to deliver them from their 
misery 
the 37yearold priest has enormous support from the people and 
has promised to sweep out tyranny and usher in an era of democratic 
rule 
but he is loathed by many of haitis traditional power brokers 
the army the business community rural landowners and roman 
catholic and protestant church leaders opponents see him as a 
populist demagogue whose presidency poses the threat of a 
theocratic dictatorship 
although official returns were not expected until late today 
international observers said aristide was projected to win sundays 
elections the countrys firstever democratic vote 
the priest has said his mission is to make life better for the 
poor the slum dwellers and peasants he has associated with for 
years 
he is slight bespectacled and softspoken yet capable of 
crowdrousing oratory 
for years he preached to the poor from a church in the capitals 
slums he shared his feelings telling his parishioners when he was 
depressed shedding tears publicly without shame he operated a 
home for streethardened boys 
he first decided to run for president to counteract the 
candidacy of roger lafontant selfproclaimed chief of the dreaded 
tonton macoute militia used by the duvaliers to terrorize the 
populace into submission 
lafontant later disqualified from running calls aristide a 
communist and has said he will block his way to the presidency 
born the son of peasants in the southern coast town of port 
salut aristide was sensitized at an early age to the countrys 
stark poverty by the roman catholic salesian order 
he joined the order in 1982 and was ousted in 1988 for 
allegedly fomenting revolution 
aristide is an advocate of liberation theology a belief popular 
among third world priests that the church should be involved in the 
struggles of the poor 
he remains a priest but cannot lead mass or deliver radio 
sermons under vatican regulations priests cannot hold public 
office and aristide has said he would quit the priesthood if he won 
the election 
jesus was not a priest he was a man fighting for justice 
he said recently 
aristide is the figurehead of a messianic movement the 
incarnation of a collective dream says laennec hurbon a 
specialist on religious movements in the caribbean his 
responsibility to his following is not the same as that of a 
politician to his constituency 
jeanclaude bajeux a human rights activist and former priest 
called aristide a great communicator 
aristide is a poet nourished by biblical imagery he is a 
master of the vernacular creole he said unlike the other 
candidates who told the people what they thought he helped the 
people express themselves 
aristide gained a nationwide following from radio broadcasts of 
his strident sermons against successive military regimes that have 
ruled haiti since jeanclaude baby doc duvalier fled the 
country in 1986 
he has been the target of three assassination attempts most 
recently in 1988 when armybacked thugs stormed his saint jean 
bosco church during mass and killed at least 12 parishioners 
aristide has not outlined a political agenda to carry out his 
campaign promises 
playing on messianic symbolism and patriotic fervor aristide 
has stumped nationwide he calls his campaign operation lavales or 
torrent its emblem is the fighting cock which represents 
haitis coming sunrise 
</TEXT>
