lothar de maiziere who a year ago led east 
germany to democracy and unity with the west has resigned from the 
reunited nations first government following allegations that he 
was once a police informant 
interior minister wolfgang schaeuble said monday there were 
indications de maiziere and a man codenamed in files of east 
germanys stasi secret police as czerny were one and the same 
he said there was no proof however that de maiziere knowingly 
worked for the secret police of the former communist nation 
de maiziere has denied the charges but resigned from chancellor 
helmut kohls government as ministerwithoutportfolio and said he 
would not be a member of kohls new cabinet 
he kept his seat in the new germany parliament but resigned his 
leadership positions in the christian democratic party 
the resignation of the softspoken de maiziere who often said 
he preferred playing viola to playing politics illustrates how 
hard it will be for the united nation to escape the repercussions 
of east germanys past 
as one of germanys truly historical figures the man who built 
and held together former east germanys young fractious democracy 
is by far the biggest casualty so far but he was not the first and 
likely wont be the last 
de maiziere a professional viola player in east german 
orchestras during the 1960s spent most of his adult life as a 
lawyer under the old communist regime a deeply religious man he 
made a name for himself by defending concientious objectors and 
political dissidents 
he also was a member of the christian democrats an approved 
relatively ineffectual party that received money from the communist 
government but put forth an image of independence 
in november 1989 after the communist hardliners were ousted by 
the peaceful revolt he was chosen to lead the party as it tried to 
remake itself in the image of its west german namesake 
when the communists agreed to free elections in march de 
maizieres party formed a coalition with two other conservative 
parties and began advocating swift unity with west germany 
another lawyer wolfgang schnur was chosen to lead the 
coalition but schnur resigned march 14 four days before the 
elections amid allegations he too had been an informant for the 
secret police 
de maiziere 50 was hastily chosen to replace him and led the 
coalition to resounding victory 
after german unification on oct 3 de maiziere was among four 
east german officials added to kohls expanded cabinet 
one day after the election new reports surfaced alleging that 
de maiziere had been a paid stasi informant who even had an 
identity card and a code name 
the government said monday the evidence was inconclusive but 
accepted his resignation schaeuble said the investigation would 
continue 
the stasi had hundreds of thousands of informants who spied on 
