<DOCNO> AP901218-0036 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
hospital records often err in listing 
medications that patients older than 65 were taking before 
admission posing a risk of serious treatment errors a study 
suggests 
sixty percent of records in the study contained at least one 
error in listing important medications and 18 percent had 
three or more errors 
the analysis excluded overthecounter drugs cold medicines and 
medications applied to the body when those drugs were included 83 
percent of hospital records contained at least one error 
mistakes in medication records mean patients may not be given 
drugs they need or they may get unneeded drugs that cause harmful 
side effects said researcher dr mark beers 
he cited the case of a patient whose records failed to note she 
was taking an oral diabetes medication the drug was not continued 
in the hospital until beers pointed out the error he said 
another patient was given a bloodthinning drug because his 
record said he was on the medication when in fact the treatment 
had been stopped months before beers said the error created a 
needless risk of bleeding beers said 
we found some really clinically very important problems that 
could lead to complications prolonged hospital stays and perhaps 
even death said beers of the university of california at los 
angeles 
i expected to find some errors but the number of people 
involved and the quantity of errors and the kinds of drugs involved 
were much greater much more serious than i had speculated beers 
said 
the study appears in the november issue of the journal of the 
american geriatrics society 
the 60 percent error rate is high enough that i think every 
patient and every doctor would agree thats scary commented dr 
jerry avorn of harvard university medical school an authority on 
medication use by the elderly 
while most such mistakes will not cause any trouble the high 
frequency means its just a matter of time and the law of 
probability that some unpleasant clinical outcome is going to 
occur he said 
part of the problem is that physicians are not as preoccupied 
as we should be with taking a medication history avorn said 
another factor is that sick or injured patients are often unable to 
give a comprehensive list of their medications avorn and beers 
said 
beers recommended that people of any age carry an updated list 
of current medications with them including the name of each drug 
the dosage and how often they take it 
he also recommended that patients older than 65 be asked a 
second time about their current medication use a day or so after 
admission by a nurse or pharmacist who can devote 15 or 20 minutes 
to a thorough interview 
the study involved 122 randomly chosen patients who were 
admitted to a university hospital or a community hospital their 
average age was 77 and all were older than 65 
the work focused on older people because they tend to use more 
medications than younger people change prescriptions more 
frequently and are more vulnerable to side effects beers said 
researchers checked records written by doctors at the time of 
admission and then carefully interviewed the patients within two 
days of admission to get their own list of medications for 
comparison 
for important medications records for 52 percent of all 
patients omitted at least one drug while records for 22 percent 
listed a drug that the patient was not actually taking 
omitting a drug not only means that a patient may not get a 
needed medication in the hospital but it also deprives doctors of 
a clue to the patients medical status beers said 
</TEXT>
