government is investigating the clash in jalapa which he said 
in no way contributes to the reconciliation and pacification of 
the country 
in a television broadcast cesar condemned a series of attacks 
on uno elected officials that began during the weekend 
a bomb destroyed the car of an uno lawmaker humberto castilla 
and part of his home in the southeastern town of juigalpa on 
saturday castilla a hardliner who pushed for the army budget 
cuts was out of the country at the time no one was hurt in the 
blast 
grenads were fired sunday and monday at the homes of several 
other coalition mayors and deputies who backed the budget cuts no 
injuries were reported in the offensive that uno blamed on army 
members 
mrs chamorro returning monday from a costa rican summit in 
which central american presidents addressed demilitarization of the 
region said she wants to reduce the sandinista armys size 
but she said we cant do things overnight 
she has cut thousands of soldiers from the ranks of the army 
and the 39member sandinista bloc in the national assembly opposed 
the military budget reduction saying it would mean firing 10000 
more 
on sunday the army took fullpage ads in prosandinista 
newspapers and ran television spots to publicize a threepage 
communique that said some legislators were pushing nicaragua into 
chaos and a bloodbath by voting for the budget reduction 
as humans that we are we cannot throw into the street the army 
or any civilian mrs chamorro said monday 
mrs chamorro is treading a fine line between the polarized 
positions of the powerful sandinista party and the 14party uno 
coalition whose 51 deputies in the 92member national assembly 
voted in unprecedented unity for the military budget cut on friday 
the leglislature includes two independents 
since taking office in april she has weathered paralyzing 
sandinista union general strikes and a series of roadblocks by 
sympathizers of former contras 
the dissidence from both sides has erupted in violence but the 
shootout sunday claimed more lives than any incident before 
