<DOCNO> AP901218-0063 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
safety of the nations nuclear weapons was not 
given the same urgency as modernization of those systems to meet 
military requirements a special review panel said today 
three of the nations leading physicists in a report to the 
house armed services committee also expressed concern over the 
absence of quantitative safety standards for the dispersal of 
plutonium 
plutonium a highly poisonous component in a nuclear device 
could be released from a weapon by a fire or conventional explosion 
as well as by an atomic explosion the panel said in its 44page 
report 
although plutonium dispersal is a much less threatening danger 
than a sizable nuclear yield it is nevertheless a potentially 
serious hazard particularly if the plutonium is aerosolized in a 
chemical detonation the panel said 
its members are dr sidney d drell deputy director of the 
stanford linear accelerator center nobel laureate dr charles h 
townes of the university of california at berkeley and dr john s 
foster head of the defense science board 
the armed services committee empaneled the three in may after 
questions were raised about the safety of several nuclear weapons 
systems including the shortrange airtoground attack missile 
known as srama 
since that time defense secretary dick cheney has taken the 
srama off alert bombers of the strategic air command 
in the report the panel said that since the 1950s and the 
height of the cold war the government gave special consideration 
to changes in the system to meet defense needs and safety was not 
treated similarly 
modernization and improvement programs gave priority to 
military requirements the report said safety in general was 
not viewed with the same urgency 
modification of the system has moved slowly and due to budget 
constraints the emphasis has been on acquiring new weapons 
in anticipation many older ones remain in todays nuclear 
stockpile that do not meet present nuclear weapons design 
criteria the panel said 
it recommended among other things that all weapons be equipped 
with modern enhanced nuclear detonation safety systems and that all 
nuclear bombs on aircraft be equipped with insensitive high 
explosives and fireresistant pits within the weapons 
these are the two most critical safety features currently 
available for avoiding plutonium dispersal in the event of aircraft 
fires or crashes the report said 
rep les aspin dwis chairman of the armed services 
committee said the report calls for a reassessment of the nations 
priorities for nuclear weapons with safety ahead of military 
effectiveness 
improvement in ussoviet relations gives us breathing space 
to begin planning now for a nuclear arsenal that is cheaper and 
smaller than the one we have today as well as safer aspin said 
the ranking republican on the committee rep william dickinson 
of alabama said the panel of physicists correctly notes that 
many of the safety problems identified to date have been or are in 
the process of being fixed nonetheless the panel did express the 
view that there is still room for improvement 
</TEXT>
