<DOCNO> AP901218-0098 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
new safeguards are necessary to prevent an 
accidental nuclear explosion involving the nations aging atomic 
weapons three leading physicists told congress on tuesday 
its not a dangerous system now but we can make it safer 
sidney d drell who headed the panel said in testimony before the 
house armed services committee 
there have been 32 accidents only two in recent years the 
panel said adding that was a relatively low number 
since the 1950s when tensions between the superpowers grew 
nuclearweapon safety wasnt given the same urgency as 
modernization of those systems the panel said in its report 
in addition modification has moved slowly and because of 
budget limitations the emphasis has been on acquiring new weapons 
in anticipation many older ones remain in todays nuclear 
stockpile that do not meet present nuclear weapons design 
criteria the report said 
recent technical advances have enabled scientists to use 
supercomputers to trace the development of a nuclear detonation in 
three dimensions rather than the previous limit of two the report 
said 
a major consequences of these results is a realization that 
unintended nuclear detonations present a greater risk than 
previously estimated and believed for some of the warheads in the 
stockpile it said 
the panel did not specify what the previous risk has been 
its members are drell deputy director of the stanford linear 
accelerator center nobel laureate charles h townes of the 
university of california at berkeley and john s foster head of 
the defense science board 
the armed services committee empaneled the three in may after 
questions were raised about the safety of several nuclear weapons 
systems including the shortrange airtoground attack missile 
known as srama 
since then defense secretary dick cheney has taken the srama 
off strategic air command alert bombers 
the panel recommended among other things that all weapons be 
equipped with modern enhanced nuclear detonation safety systems and 
that all nuclear bombs on aircraft be equipped with insensitive 
high explosives and fireresistant pits within the weapons 
a point of contention is the navys trident d5 missile whose 
nuclear warheads arent equipped with insensitive high explosives 
the warheads also are located near a thirdstage rocket motor 
which has a high energy propellant that could detonate in an 
accident 
drell suggested redesigning the d5 missile with the special 
explosives and putting a nondetonable propellant in the rocket 
motor 
the panel also recommended the creation of a special adversary 
group to examine and challenge nuclear weapons design and a joint 
advisory committee to report directly to the secretaries of defense 
and energy 
the agencies said in a onepage statement they would review the 
recommendations and called the panels goals consistent with both 
departments established priorities for safety 
rep john spratt dsc chairman of the armed services panel 
on department of energy nuclear facilities said the committees 
concern is not to condemn the nuclear community or establishment 
but to see that safety is pushed to the limit 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

