serves as supreme commander of the armed forces 
defense minister gen veljko kadijevic created a stir this month 
when he suggested the army might intervene directly to preserve the 
federation 
earlier tuesday the influential constitutional commission of 
yugoslavias parliament appealed for a peaceful negotiated 
solution to the power struggle between different republics 
it said parliament should meet dec 27 to discuss how the 
country could stay united while the six republics work out 
yugoslavias future an agreement should be ratified by mid1991 
after elections for a federal parliament it said 
fear of an imminent breakup or of an armed struggle has grown 
since serbias president slobodan milosevic and his former 
communists resoundingly won the first round of the republics free 
elections dec 9 
the us central intelligence agency recently predicted 
yugoslavia may disintegrate within 18 months and civil war could 
break out 
the second round of elections sunday in serbia and procommunist 
montenegro coincides with slovenias scheduled vote on whether 
slovenia becomes fully independent 
croatia and slovenia where centerright parties ousted 
communists in spring elections have threatened to secede serbia 
and montenegro favor a strong federal government 
slovenias senior leaders on tuesday told a news conference in 
their capital of ljubljana the plebiscite does not mean 
secession tanjug said 
it said president milan kucan prime minister lojze peterle and 
the chief of parliament franc bucar assured reporters nothing 
earthshaking or undemocratic would happen after the referendum 
opinion polls have suggested slovenians will vote overwhelmingly 
for independence but the plebiscite is seen as a lastditch effort 
to get other republics to agree to a new loose confederation 
rather than a step toward immediate secession 
the presidency acknowledges that each republic has a 
constitutional right to secede but only after consultations with 
the other five republics 
it said that implementing the principle of selfdetermination 
of the people without going by regulations set out by the 
constitution and the law is unacceptable 
slovenias plans crudely reject and practically thwart the 
initiative launched by the presidency of yugoslavia to rearrange 
yugoslavia in a peaceful democratic legal manner based 
on the constitution it said 
the presidency decides by majority vote and never announces 
whether there are dissenting votes 
the other two republics are bosnia and herezegovina and 
macedonia 
