<TEXT>
the interstate commerce commission voted 
unanimously tuesday to ban smoking on all regularly scheduled 
interstate buses in the united states 
bus companies were given the option of allowing charter 
passengers to smoke if the chartering group agrees it should be 
permitted 
the ban will take effect soon after the issuance of the 
commissions decision in writing and its publication in the federal 
register according to icc spokesman a dennis watson 
lawyers for the icc said the change was supported by a wide 
variety of groups but was opposed by the tobacco industry 
john banzhaf executive director of action on smoking and 
health the organization whose request initiated the icc action 
praised the decision 
smokers can refrain from smoking for several hours and light 
up at bus stops but nonsmokers cannot similarly refrain from 
breathing banzhaf said 
the icc lawyers contended that smoking has been proved to be 
injurious to health and that tobacco smoke cannot be adequately 
ventilated from buses to assure the health and comfort of 
nonsmokers 
the commission began its consideration of a smoking ban last 
march at the request of the american bus association and united bus 
owners of america the national trade associations for the 
intercity bus business 
in april action on smoking and health ash an antismoking 
association filed a similar request but asked that it be imposed 
on all buses including charters 
officials for the bus industry contended that operators of 
charter buses should be permitted to regulate smoking based on 
their passengers desires 
the commission lawyers said officials of the nations charter 
bus industry said they feared some business would be lost i they 
were compelled to enforce a uniform nonsmoking ban 
the icc nosmoking rule affects passengers served by about 300 
bus companies that provide service on interstate routes in 1990 
these companies are expected to serve some 24 million passengers 
greyhound the nations largest bus company banned smoking on 
its own initiative shortly after the icc began considering the 
issue 
as the regulatory process unfolded this year ash contended that 
bus passengers are entitled to the same protection from tobacco 
smoke in the air as those who travel by plane and train 
it noted that amtrak recently banned smoking in the last four 
rows of its superliner lounge cars and in most of its train 
stations there are still smoking cars on trains 
smoking is banned on almost all domestic airline flights the 
only exceptions are flights to alaska and hawaii each lasting more 
than six hours overseas flights are not affected 
ash said that a recent study of air quality in airline passenger 
cabins showed that as many as 440 nonsmokers a year would die of 
cancer if smokers were to continue to light up aboard flights 
lasting two hours or longer 
the antismoking group said bus passengers would be at even 
higher risk if smoking were to continue 
it said the smaller seating capacity of buses forces nonsmoking 
passengers to be seated closer to smokers than on planes it also 
said ventilation on buses often is inferior to that on airplanes 
and it said buses are often the only affordable means of 
longdistance transportation for the poor and elderly 
the bus trade associations also cited the health issue but they 
contended a clear federal prohibition would also eliminate any 
misunderstanding in the effort of individual bus companies to 
enforce limitations on smoking 
they said the current rule limiting smoking to no more than 30 
percent of bus seats is hard to enforce and that efforts by some 
companies to ban smoking could place them at a disadvantage if 
competitors advertised that smoking was permitted 
the tobacco industry contended that health hazards posed to 
nonsmokers on interstate buses are not proved 
</TEXT>
