<TEXT>
boston police violated individual civil rights in 
using stopandsearch tactics and appeared to have coerced 
witnesses to testify in the stuart murder case the massachusetts 
attorney general said tuesday 
in a report based on a nearly yearlong investigation james 
shannon said he found a broad pattern of civil rights infringements 
in search tactics in which police randomly stopped and frisked 
minority youths in bostons inner city 
police commissioner francis roache called shannons allegations 
totally unjustified and completely lacking in due process 
the murder of sevenmonthspregnant carol stuart who was white 
in october 1989 generated widespread publicity her husband 
charles who was seriously wounded told police a black mugger 
abducted them in their car and shot them 
william bennett a black man whom police were investigating in 
connection with the shooting was absolved when charles stuart 
jumped to his death off a bridge and police implicated him in his 
wifes slaying 
shannon who leaves office jan 3 stopped short of bringing 
court action saying such a move would prove timeconsuming and 
ineffective instead he recommended that a civilian review board 
be established to monitor police 
before the stuart slaying black community leaders complained 
that police wrongly stopped and searched black youths the outcry 
intensified when police seeking a suspect in the stuart case 
kicked down doors and stripsearched young black men 
there is no excuse for forcing young men to lower their 
trousers or for a police officer to search inside their underwear 
on public streets and hallways shannon said in the report 
that practice must be condemned in the strongest possible 
terms 
roache in a statement issued after shannons report was 
released stressed that no one has filed a complaint against the 
department 
it is crucial to note that the attorney general has concluded 
that there are no grounds for any legal action the statement 
said 
the report found that homicide detectives appeared to have 
threatened coerced or offered favors to obtain testimony that 
would implicate bennett shannon said his report on the allegations 
of coercion was incomplete because police had refused to cooperate 
with the probe 
but two men who were picked up by police for questioning dereck 
jackson and eric whitney told investigators police threatened them 
with jail and denied them access to attorneys 
jackson and whitney were questioned by police after jackson told 
whitney he had heard william bennetts nephew jokingly say he 
thought bennett killed stuart 
shannon said complaints about searches should be referred to his 
office or the us attorneys office to be evaluated in the past 
the police departments internal affairs unit has overseen such 
inquiries 
but internal affairs has not done the job here shannon 
said until the bpd has demonstrated that it can police its own 
officers effectively it must be carefully scrutinized by an 
independent law enforcement agency 
shannon denied that his report was little more than a slap on 
the wrist for police who are under no obligation to abide by its 
recommendations 
litigation would accomplish nothing shannon said i think 
the public is going to demand these changes the findings are so 
substantial that they cannot be ignored 
louis elisa head of the boston chapter of the national 
association for the advancement of colored people praised shannon 
for his comprhensive review 
but he said the report came so late in shannons term and 
suggested that shannon pass his findings on to the us attorney to 
take action 
shannon alleged in the report that frank mcgee a lawyer for the 
boston police patrolmens association advised officers not to 
cooperate with the investigation 
mcgee said the allegations were false and that shannon was 
retaliating for the unions endorsement of scott harshbarger who 
defeated shannon in the attorney general race 
