<TEXT>
robert fisk one of the last western journalists 
left in the cauldron of beirut believes quite a lot could have 
stayed if done with great caution and care 
but as fisks justpublished book makes clear luck and 
instinct are equally important for a risktakers survival in the 
killing fields of lebanon the braking of a car just before a round 
explodes in its path the precious inches separating the quick and 
the dead during an artillery barrage or car bombing the fortuitous 
intervention of an outsider in the midst of triggerhappy gunmen 
pity the nation published by atheneum relates in often 
gory detail the nearmisses fear and horror fisk experienced and 
witnessed during his 14 years of covering civil war two israeli 
invasions the massacre at the sabra and chatila refugee camps and 
bombings of the us embassy and marine barracks in lebanon 
the book is subtitled the abduction of lebanon an allusion 
to repeated disastrous foreign interventions in the ancient land 
of cedars whose revenge was to welcome all her invaders and kiss 
them to death 
a reviewer of the books british edition who had followed fisks 
adventurous reportage for the times of london and later the 
independent confessed i am amazed to see that he is still 
alive and writing 
the 44yearold british correspondent says the book was inspired 
in part by his friend and colleague terry anderson the associated 
press middle east correspondent who was kidnapped on a west beirut 
street in march 1985 anderson the longest held of 13 western 
hostages in lebanon paid the price for staying on the story 
fisk wrote 
fisk stayed because he too felt a commitment to a protracted 
violent story which you cant cover long range 
andersons dignified behavior in captivity has done nothing 
but enhance the standing of journalists fisk said in an 
interview i hear nothing bad said about terry in beirut 
fisk himself narrowly averted abducion by gunmen a year earlier 
after a french connectionlike car chase through the darkened 
streets of west beirut 
in his book fisk writes that andersons kidnappers were not the 
faceless terrorists the reagan administration professed them to 
be 
his principal captor was so well known that american agents 
tried to arrest him near paris when he was on holiday in france 
the french mindful of their own hostages forced the americans to 
leave him alone fisk wrote 
western intelligence agencies have fingered imad mughniyeh 
leader of the islamic jihad as the probable mastermind behind 
scores of kidnappings including that of anderson mughniyeh is 
wanted by the united states in the 1985 hijacking of a twa jetliner 
in which a us navy diver was killed 
fisks book is critical of the lowprofile approach taken by the 
associated press in the immediate aftermath of andersons 
kidnapping fisk favored a direct personal appeal for aid to 
syrian president hafez assad whose troops control a wide area of 
lebanon 
andersons kidnapping prompted most western news organizations 
to withdraw their american and european staffers from beirut fisk 
and his wife lara marlowe of the financial times wound up as the 
last western correspondents living in moslem west beirut 
toward the end of the book fisk writes it seemed that 
lebanon had become an epic of lost souls of missing men and women 
people who had disappeared had been arrested and not returned 
kidnapped tortured dead 
nearly six years after andersons kidnapping fisk reports 
the traditional respect for journalists as impartial observers is 
not dead though critically damaged in lebanon 
but he sees signs of hope now that moslem and christian militia 
men are withdrawing from beirut some areas are safer than a year 
ago at the moment it has gotten a lot less worrisome to report if 
they the lebanese combatants are sure of your good intentions 
fisk said 
fisks reporting from the arab side of the middle east conflict 
has led some israeli officials and supporters to challenge fisks 
good intentions and objectivity israeli president chaim herzog is 
quoted in the book as telling his irish counterpart garret 
firzgerland in 1985 that fisk was a virulent hater of israel 
fisk was then also writing for the irish times 
all journalists who work in the arab world are forced to 
report what they see fisk said if israeli air raids killed 
women and children it was our duty to report it you cannot change 
the rules and integrity of your profession if you happen to report 
on israel in an arab country 
while the bulk of the book deals critically with the 1982 
israeli invasion of lebanon and its bitter consequences fisk also 
disapproves of the conduct of the palestinians the syrians the 
various lebanese militias and the united states us troops who 
came as peacekeepers and left as combatants were withdrawn from 
beirut after the 1983 truckbombing of the us marine barracks 
killed 241 americans 
fisk sees some parallels between american entanglement in the 
lebanese conflict and their present buildup in the persian gulf 
fisk refers in the book to the american onetwothree school of 
politics which we in beirut so derided military action followed 
by political aims followed by a solution 
the gulf buildup he said involves the same illusion the 
notion that the united states can remain israels best friend and 
still be the honest broker in the middle east 
