<TEXT>
among inhouse white house headaches a 
reversed ruling against minority scholarships is likely to prove 
more troublesome for president bush than the embarrassment of 
naming a republican party chairman who quit before taking the job 
both episodes point to disarray in an administration undergoing 
some secondyear remodeling both were the sort of surprises 
presidents do not like both came in areas where the white house 
already had problems civil rights and political management 
bush got no warning and there was no consultation with his top 
aides before an assistant education secretary ruled that 
scholarships reserved for blacks and other minorities were out of 
bounds at colleges and universities that receive federal funds the 
same official overhauled his ruling on tuesday at white house 
insistence the new version permits such scholarships so long as 
they are privately financed 
bush said he didnt think it was a flipflop 
there was a flipflop though the politically awkward exit of 
william j bennett two weeks after bush announced he wanted the 
former drug policy boss to become chairman of the republican 
national committee 
bennett withdrew on dec 13 saying a second reading by the 
white house lawyer raised doubt that he could properly accept 
speechmaking and consulting fees during the next year if he took 
the job 
it was his old government job not the party position that 
posed the problem federal ethics law forbids former federal 
officials from lobbying their old colleagues on behalf of private 
employers for a year after leaving office in bennetts case that 
could have been construed as applying to contacts he might have 
made as party chairman on matters of interest to private 
organizations that paid him for speeches 
the party job pays 125000 a year and other chairman in both 
parties have earned outside income to add to their salaries 
bennett said the difference is that they came out of private life 
not executive branch jobs 
bennett made 240000 in speech fees during the four months he 
was out of the government between tours as ronald reagans 
secretary of education and bushs drug policy director he also has 
a book contract that paid him an advance of 187500 
his circumstances didnt change during the three weeks from 
choice to announcement to withdrawal the advice changed 
bennett said in withdrawing 
a president ought to be able to count on better more durable 
advice than that when he chooses somebody for an appointment the 
bennett affair drew taunts from democrats and from conservative 
republicans as well 
the conservatives first suspected that the choice of bennett was 
an attempt to control a voice that might have joined theirs in 
dissent against bush for what some of them say is a turn away from 
ronald reagans legacy when he withdrew they began suggesting 
that bennett had been pushed because he wasnt willing to take his 
commands from john h sununu the white house chief of staff 
john sununu is a close friend of mine bennett said he is 
and this is a message partly to my fellow conservatives one of 
the best and most longstanding conservatives in america 
except as a political footnote that chapter will close when the 
republican national committee confirms bushs backup choice for 
chairman on jan 25 
the scholarship issue may persist although the administration 
got it turned around before congress convened recess hearings on 
the subject it may well come up again next year when 
congressional democrats renew their drive for the civil rights bill 
they could not push past a bush veto this fall 
the democrats say the initial ruling against racebased 
scholarships fits the pattern set in republican administrations 
and they may write into their 1991 bill a provision to guarantee 
that colleges and universities can reserve scholarships for blacks 
and other minority students 
bush said he thinks the scholarship question eventually will be 
settled by the courts he said he might be open to legislation on 
it the president praised michael j williams assistant secretary 
of education for civil rights who issued the ruling and the 
amendments williams a black lawyer with a long record in civil 
rights said he had been naive not to anticipate the controversy 
theres more of it coming 
 
editors note walter r mears vice president and columnist 
for the associated press has reported on washington and national 
politics for more than 25 years 
