<TEXT>
piles of garbage choke streets drug 
deals and murders are common housing projects have been flooded 
with raw sewage and weedinfested vacant lots checker the city 
east st louis is a 47 million sinkhole a city so burdened by 
debt that some of its police cars lack tail lights and city hall 
was sold to pay a court judgment 
to mike riddle its a place where houses fall down and nothing 
comes back up 
when they tear down a house they dont put another one up 
and the weeds just take over its just rundown said riddle a 
school custodianand longtime resident 
to sandra woods its a place so rough that cabbies wont come 
when called fear of crime makes for sleepless nights and her 
grandchildren wait in the rain for school buses that dont run on 
time 
its pitiful she said 
east st louis once was bustling with chemical metal and glass 
works but labor troubles crime and corruption in the 1960s led to 
white flight the population was 82000 in 1960 but has shrunk to 
40000 today the city is virtually all black 
the citys 63 slayings in 1989 gave it the highest percapita 
murder rate in the fbis national rankings and police say they are 
overwhelmed by drugrelated crime residents talk about their fears 
of gang fights and driveby shootings 
last year east st louis crumbling sewers flooded a school and 
a housing project with raw sewage the city in january was 
convicted of reckless conduct for endangering police officers by 
failing to outfit squad cars with working radios head and tail 
lights and other basics 
east st louis has so little money that a judge awarded its 6 
million city hall building as a damage payment to a man who was 
beaten in the city jail by another inmate the beating victim has 
sold the building to an undisclosed buyer but the city is 
appealing the damage award 
in the poorest parts of town drivers inch cars between 
3foothigh piles of trash that squeeze streets to one lane two 
years ago the city stopped picking up garbage and people cant 
pay anyone else to do it 
burned and abandoned downtown buildings are left to rot and 
fall within sight of the skyscrapers and gateway arch of more 
prosperous st louis across the mississippi river 
potholes create caverns in virtually every street and on some 
days the air stings with the smoke of burning tires dumped and 
torched in vacant lots 
there are bright spots in some neighborhoods the ranchstyle 
homes are lovingly maintained with flower beds manicured lawns 
and freshly paved driveways 
but bars over the windows tell of the citys dangers and next 
to a house that would fit in any middleclass suburb is a 
dilapidated home with a junked car outside 
such contrasts are the legacy of those who refuse to leave and 
those who cant 
a lot of people stay here because they cant afford to go 
anywhere else said russell hudlin president of the chamber of 
commerce and owner of a gas station and convenience store 
others stay because the city offers familiarity proximity to 
jobs and shopping in st louis and a thriving night life hudlin 
said 
downtown east st louis many bars offer rhythm and blues 
liquor and liveliness long after st louis clubs must close 
hudlin considers the night life a chance for municipal growth 
but the city cannot raise enough revenue to make improvements or 
hire workers despite having one of the highest property tax rates 
in the state homeowners pay 950 for every 100 of assessed 
value 
most major industries sit outside the city limits providing no 
tax base and its estimated that more than half of city residents 
get government aid 
in 1989 132 percent of east st louis residents were without 
work not including the chronically unemployed or those on welfare 
according to the illinois department of employment security 
city officials now pin their hopes on gambling and the state 
east st louis has been chosen to receive one of five riverboat 
gambling licenses in illinois and pending state approval of 
private operators officials hope to develop a riverboat port 
within a few years 
the city also expects 34 million in state loans including 4 
million for immediate needs such as police and firefighting 
equipment road repairs and garbage pickup the rest will be used 
for longterm improvements and debt consolidation 
the entire sum being raised by a statebacked bond issue must 
be repaid over several decades 
the catch is that the mayor and aldermanic council must get 
their annual budget approved by a stateappointed bailout 
authority and spending is monitored by an investment banking firm 
working for the state 
if the state doesnt like the budget it can take control of 
city finances and intercept bailout payments 
the authority has been holding back a 375 millionloan 
installment because the city missed the deadline to submit its 1991 
budget the aldermanic council this month finally approved a 57 
millionbudget at the demand of the authority 
last month residents voted to have city officials hire a 
professional city manager 
on the whole we are at ground zero and we can only go up 
said hudlin the chamber of commerce head you can only imagine 
if we pay our debts and get back on our feet again what we can 
do 
riddle seemed to agree as he stood across the street from a 
vacant lot and abandoned building 
i believe the people of east st louis dont give a hoot who 
owns the city they just want to see it improve he said 
theres a lot of people who love this city 
