<TEXT>
some bankers say theyre willing to chip in more 
to help rescue the governments ailing deposit insurance fund but 
say they want substantial reforms in banking regulations 
federal deposit insurance corp chairman william seidman on 
monday floated a proposal to boost the insurance fund by 24 
billion 
the proposal comes as industry officials and regulators ponder 
ideas to dramatically restructure the nations banks which have 
been beset by a stagnant economy strong foreign competition 
declining real estate values and rising loan defaults 
in the past 3 years 734 banks with 102 billion in total 
assets have failed according to the federal deposit insurance 
corp the failures have drained the governments deposit insurance 
fund from 183 billion in 1987 to an estimated 9 billion this 
year the fdic reported the fund is used to repay up to 100000 
in individual deposits in the event of a bank failure 
i think theres no question the fund needs to be replenished 
that one way or another the industry is going to have to pay for 
it thats been the history since its been established said 
john rau president and chief executive officer of lasalle national 
bank in chicago 
but bankers say if theyre asked to help rescue the fund they 
want federal banking laws reformed they complain that current 
regulations hamper them from competing with securities firms and 
other large corporations that offer loans credit cards and other 
such financial services 
richard a kirk president of american bankers association said 
any deposit insurance rescue must come with modernization of 
the financial system if future problems are to be prevented 
kirk and others dont question the fdics grim predictions of 
the funds solvency but says the banking industry overall is 
healthy the nations 12400 banks enjoyed a 13 percent increase in 
profits for the third quarter of 1990 he said 
seidman in prepared testimony before the house banking 
subcommittee on financial institutions fell short of endorsing the 
24 billion plan 
a similar strategy was used in 1984 when congress voted to 
strengthen the credit union fund under the bill credit unions 
were required to deposit 1 percent of insured shares into the fund 
he said 
seidman also suggested annual deposit insurance premiums should 
be raised to 23 cents per 100 in deposits he also discussed other 
options such as requiring banks to buy preferred stock in the 
fdic 
he said the proposals would add only marginally to bank 
failures 
that view was disputed however by three private economists 
r dan brumbaugh of san francisco robert litan of the brookings 
institution and james barth of auburn university who presented a 
report to the house panel 
brumbaugh said a one percent assessment on deposits would cost 
banks the equivalent of two years of earnings litan said it would 
cause additional failures costing 3 billion to 8 billion 
seidman also raised the possibility that regulators may hold off 
shutting down weak banks that appear likely to recover citing the 
success of such a policy toward struggling farm banks in the 
mid1980s 
many bankers declined to comment on seidmans statements until 
they had a chance to review the proposals in detail 
our reaction in general has always been that every participant 
in the financial services industry should be regulated by the same 
standards said fraser seitel spokesman for chase manhattan 
corp he like others in the industry endorses changes in banking 
regulations to provide a level playing field with nonfinancial 
corporations that provide some financial services 
they object for example that atampt can offer its universal 
credit card without facing the same regulations as banks 
fritz elmendorf spokesman for the consumer bankers association 
in arlington va said most bankers are willing to pay more into 
the fund and avoid a taxpayer bailout along the lines of the 
savings and loan scandal failures of the nations savings and 
loans are estimated to cost the nations taxpayers billions of 
dollars 
its an argument on how much the industry can truly afford 
and thats where its unclear said elmendorf 
</TEXT>
