<TEXT>
zenith electronics corp may have leapfrogged 
into the lead of the highdefinition television race with a 
proposed alldigital system that offers better picture resolution 
than its competitors analysts said 
on paper it still looks to me like the best of the 
proposals james magid an analyst with needham amp co in new 
york said of the project that zenith and american telephone amp 
telegraph co announced monday 
the hdtv system that zenith is developing jointly with the atampt 
would transmit 1575 horizontal picture lines every onethirtieth 
of a second compared with competing systems based on 1125 or 1050 
lines the pictures on todays tv sets are composed of 300 
horizontal lines 
the companies are competing with four other groups for the 
coveted hdtv standard to be selected by the federal communications 
commission 
the standard will be the sole format used by cable satellite 
and major commercial networks to provide americans with the 
crystalclear pictures and compactdiscquality sound of hdtv 
analysts said zenith had to come up with an alldigital system 
to keep pace with two other contenders general instruments corp 
and a consortium of nv philips of the netherlands thomson of 
france the nbc network and the david sarnoff research center 
which previously made alldigital proposals 
the other contenders for the hdtv standard are the japan 
broadcasting corp and the massachusetts institute of technology 
fully digital systems can transmit hdtv signals in the ones and 
zeros of computer language making for clear reception even on the 
fringe of a broadcasters range zenith previously had proposed a 
partially digital system 
david lauchenbruch editorial director of television digest an 
industry journal said zenith appears to have caught up with its 
competitors in the alldigital area and may have surpassed them in 
picture resolution 
but he noted that the systems relative merits wont really be 
known until the fcc tests them one by one beginning next april 
these things i think exist mainly on computers 
lauchenbruch said 
zenith spokesman john taylor said zenith and atampt already were 
working toward an alldigital or mostly digital system prior to the 
proposals made earlier this year by general instruments and the 
philips consortium 
we did it to reap the benefits of digital technology to 
provide interferencefree and snowfree pictures taylor said 
the test period for zeniths system begins in late october 
taylor said the fcc hopes to select a standard by june 1993 
backers of hdtv say it could revitalize segments of the us 
electronics industry and through military educational and 
medical spinoffs be the linchpin for us economic growth in the 
next century 
zenith the last major usbased television manufacturer is 
gambling heavily on its system being chosen as the hdtv standard 
the company sold its computer division in 1989 and has committed 
50 million to hdtv research in which it is cooperating with atampt 
and its bell labs subsidiary 
