<TEXT>
private deposit insurance funds have not 
had a tremendous track record bank runs have brought down insurers 
in ohio and maryland and now the collapse of a small rhode island 
bank threatens another 
nonetheless as rhode island regulators piece together the 
remnants of heritage loan and investment co and the private 
agency that insured it proposals are being floated to spin off 
federal deposit insurance to the private sector 
proponents say the idea is to reform a system that allowed a 
debacle such as the savings and loan scandal 
our first line of belief is private insurance can handle the 
whole thing said dwayne welsh general counsel of the national 
deposit insurance corp of dublin ohio the way youre going to 
solve this insurance problem is privatize this thing and charge 
people depositors for the insurance 
welsh whose firm is the largest of 10 private insurers of 
credit unions in the country warns that without reform the 
federal deposit insurance corp protector of americans 
commercial bank deposits could go the way of the nowdefunct 
federal savings and loan insurance corp 
he thinks the sampllike failures in ohio maryland and rhode 
island were anomalies created by criminal wrongdoing or by state 
and federal regulators more intent on satisfying politicians 
demands than on policing an industry 
a private company he argued would be insulated from that kind 
of pressure to prop up a failing institution 
his opinion is far from universal 
people are just looking around for ways to bring market 
discipline to the system and private deposit insurance is a thing 
that a lot of academics have suggested said ellen lamb of the 
conference of state bank supervisors based in washington its a 
good theory but weve seen a lot of cases where it doesnt work 
the most recent case has been at heritage loan a small 
operation in providences federal hill neighborhood the base for 
new england organized crime 
news reports have linked bank president joseph mollicone jr 
for whom an arrest warrant has been issued with mob figures but 
lawenforcement authorities shy away from revealing details of 
their investigations 
heritages insurer the rhode island share and deposit indemnity 
corp pumped cash into the bank but that seriously drained 
risdics 25 million fund covering 16 billion in deposits at 35 
credit unions and 11 banks in the state most of the members of 
risdic since have applied for federal coverage although some of 
the credit unions are looking to walshs private fund 
peter nevola risdic president said he believed his members 
applied to the federal system reluctantly because state 
regulators suggested that otherwise they would sometime down the 
line have no insurance 
but he argues the heritage crisis proved the soundness of his 
type of fund when its reserves dipped below 1 percent of all 
member institutions deposits the banks and credit unions were 
reassessed to replenish the capital and all heritage depositors are 
recovering their money and no taxpayers are footing the bill he 
said 
i think were demonstrating that its probably the best idea 
yet he said 
nonetheless the crisis has led rhode island leaders to wonder 
whether the private insurance fund has outlived its usefulness and 
whether federal coverage should be required 
i think those kinds of questions are going to be asked again 
this year said gov edward d diprete who conceded that simply 
transferred potential problems onto the backs of taxpayers 
thats who pays for most things around here the governor 
said 
business regulation director frederick j franklin said he has 
seen a trend away from private insurance to federal insurance 
that was largely what happened after private funds in ohio and 
maryland were seriously depleted by crises in 1985 but as rhode 
islands small banks and credit unions look toward protecting their 
deposits with the treasurybacked funds fundamental questions 
about the soundness of the federal insurance are being debated 
three separate studies examining the health of the nations 
deposit insurance are to be completed during the next several 
months reforming the existing system is likely to dominate the 
next session of congress 
its no 1 on the agenda for the house banking committee 
everybodys going to jump into it said tom seppy a staffer on 
the panels subcommittee regulating financial institutions which 
commissioned one of the studies 
either supplementing or replacing the existing funds with 
private insurance is just one of the many ideas being offered but 
it is one that has aroused plenty of interest among people who 
believe the government failed to safeguard taxpayers when the sampls 
spun out of control and took a big chunk of the treasury along with 
them 
currently the mood if you will on capitol hill seems to be 
to find some way to limit the governments risk or exposure due to 
bank failures said david barr an fdic spokesman in washington 
to this point nothing is really being endorsed over another 
idea 
