<TEXT>
industrial output in germanys five new 
eastern states has dropped nearly 50 percent from 1989 the 
economics ministry said tuesday 
the figures clearly show that the new eastern states remain in a 
serious restructuring process as they move from a centrally 
controlled economy to a market economy the report said 
the industrial output dropped 35 percent from autumn of 1989 to 
july and decreased another 14 percent from july to august the 
report said however output increased about 25 percent in 
september and another one percent in october 
the report attributed the slight improvement to a 95 percent 
increase in energy production and a 21 percent increase in the 
production of foodstuffs 
no data was available to determine if the big drop of output in 
the summer months was traceable to seasonal factors 
it was also not clear whether the slight increase in production 
was due to a reorientation of consumers toward easternmade 
products after a rush to buy western products following monetary 
union on july 1 the report said 
separately the report said that new orders for production 
dropped 15 percent in august from july and another 10 percent from 
august to september 
however new orders for industrial products increased by 2 
percent from september to october 
east germanys industrial output started sagging last fall when 
tens of thousands of mostly skilled young workers fled to the 
west the problem was compounded when the borders were opened 
giving easterners free access to betterquality western products in 
former west germany which for the most part had been denied them 
for four decades 
after monetary union when the west german mark became the 
official currency western products took over many shelves in the 
east further cutting demand for locally produced items 
experts have predicted that many of former east germanys 
outdated factories and other businesses will be forced to shut down 
in the restructuring process and that up to half of the estimated 
8 million workers in the eastern states could be jobless by the end 
of 1991 
