<TEXT>
visions of pizza parlors danced in the heads of the managers at 
panteras a small midwest restaurant chain that borrowed 65 
million during the easymoney 80s to buy much larger pizza inn 
inc 
but first they overvalued and then mismanaged the dallasbased 
chain of 600 restaurants morale deteriorated training evaporated 
employees quit franchisers pulled out 
in october 1989 2 years after the leveraged buyout pizza inn 
couldnt pay debts and sought protection from creditors under 
chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code new management was 
appointed and creditors were paid about 150 restaurants closed 
but today pizza inn survives 
i was amazed at the opportunity this provides a company to 
save the baby and not liquidate the whole thing company 
president jeff rogers said the bankruptcy gave us a clean 
start 
pizza inn is a parable for the 1980s in which wideeyed 
managements exploited loose credit to expand via lbos financed by 
highrisk junk bonds the moral is found in the companys recovery 
under americas benevolent bankruptcy code 
the term bankruptcy is derived from the italian banca rotta 
which means broken bench in medieval times if a trader couldnt 
pay creditors they smashed his trading bench for centuries in 
britain debtors went to prison 
but us bankruptcy law was designed to allow companies to rise 
from the ashes of collapse the belief that failure is a forgivable 
outgrowth of entrepreneurship is considered uniquely american 
the 1990s are putting that notion to test an ailing real estate 
market lbo debts tightening bank credit increased foreign 
competition and new legal tactics are straining the nations 
bankruptcy system as never before 
federal statistics show more than 725000 business and personal 
bankruptcies were filed in the year ended june 30 double the 1981 
figure ten of the 25 biggest bankruptcies in history have occurred 
in the last 18 months beard group inc a washington research 
firm reports dun amp bradstreet corp says 55000 businesses failed 
in the first 11 months of 1990 165 a day 
we just ran out of space in our file room in phoenix for 
1990 said kevin obrien clerk for arizonas two bankruptcy 
courts if nothing happens soon we wont have anywhere to put 
91 
arizona is inundated with bankruptcies stemming from the 
collapse of the real estate and savings amp loan industries annual 
filings have more than quadrupled since 1980 to a projected 18500 
in 1990 the states five judges handled 216 chapter 11 cases 
apiece in 1989 three times the national norm 
in new york handwritten signs point to rooms containing the 
files of bigname bankruptcies such as eastern airlines drexel 
burnham lambert lomas financial and ames department stores boxes 
of documents are stacked in hallways 
bankruptcy ironically has spawned a vibrant industry 
corporate debt restructuring is one of the few growth areas at wall 
street investment houses workout firms help companies 
repackage debt to delay payments without declaring chapter 11 
businesses even have sprung up to help manage the regulatory and 
paperwork maze finding opportunity in others misfortune 
speculators invest and trade in the debt of distressed companies 
law firms are bulking up what 10 years ago was a necessary but 
unglamorous area many specialists in the field say bankruptcy law 
is to the 1990s what mergers and acquisitions law was to the 1980s 
its a hot area because of economic necessity said alan 
miller a partner at the new york law firm of weil gotschal amp 
manges which has the nations largest bankruptcy group 
the first permanent federal bankruptcy law was enacted in 1898 
but was based on the british model under which creditors forced 
companies into liquidation to collect debts the idea of using 
bankruptcy to help companies survive wasnt enshrined in the law 
until 1938 
us bankruptcy statutes remained unchanged for another 40 
years until congress in 1978 overhauled the depressionera laws to 
account for the nations more sophisticated business environment 
under the reform business reorganizations of all sizes were 
combined into chapter 11 of the bankruptcy code existing 
management was allowed to run a company during bankruptcy instead 
of a courtappointed trustee 
but none of the reformers envisioned todays multibilliondollar 
cases with multiple tiers of complicated debt and more creditor 
committees than teams in the national hockey league 
when i became a judge in 1973 i never heard of a junk bond 
said robert l ordin who stepped down from the los angeles 
bankruptcy bench in 1983 and now is with the law firm loeb amp loeb 
the costs of reorganizing in bankruptcy court also have 
escalated a typical case spins off big paychecks for attorneys 
investment bankers and accountants those fees can siphon millions 
of dollars from a debtors estate that could otherwise be used to 
pay creditors 
the costs for big companies are simply off the charts said 
stephen weinroth chairman of integrated resources inc which 
staggered into bankruptcy court 10 months ago 16 billion in debt 
the financial firm expects to spend more than 50 million on 
professional fees during its reorganization 
drexel is paying up to 18 million every three months to 
professionals hired by three creditors committees and a 
shareholders committee including those hired by drexel about 20 
law firms four accounting agencies and three investment advisers 
are involved in the bankruptcy 
some judges are fighting back in the drexel case judge howard 
buschman iii slashed lawyers fee requests by 25 percent in north 
carolina judges are forcing debtors and creditors to streamline 
cases to save time and money for smaller companies 
the chapter 11 law was designed for the large corporation 
said judge a thomas small in raleigh nc who has cut case 
completion time to six months from the national average of 18 to 24 
months it just doesnt fit for small ones 
in a chapter 11 companies continue operating but all debts and 
other legal obligations are put on hold creditors fight with the 
debtor and each other over who gets how much secured creditors 
such as banks are first in line shareholders typically are last 
the two sides negotiate and vote on a reorganization plan 
but the process can be nasty bankruptcy disputes increasingly 
are feeding a wave of legal wrangling that can prolong cases 
sometimes by years 
its become way too litigious said harry dixon chairman of 
the american bankruptcy institute even as recently as five years 
ago lawyers and judges got together and these things got settled 
with a great deal less expense than today 
one increasingly popular method of speeding the process is the 
prepackaged bankruptcy in which the debtor and creditors agree on 
a reorganization plan before declaring chapter 11 southland corp 
owner of 7eleven stores is in a prepackaged bankruptcy now 
it cuts down on the amount of fees and costs involved judges 
love them said thomas salerno a phoenix lawyer who shepherded 
signmaker kroy inc through a prepackaged bankruptcy in six 
months 
but new techniques alone arent enough demand is growing for 
reform and more judges experts predict the number of chapter 11 
filings to increase as more companies fail to honor debt 
obligations 
about 23 billion in highinterest junk bonds went into default 
in 1990 said richard lehmann editor of the defaulted bond 
newsletter a miami lakes fla trade publication another 50 
billion is expected to default in 1991 and 1992 
theres a lot of this stuff out there and we dont know how 
its going to shake out said nathan c thorne head of 
restructuring at merrill lynch amp co its like a snake just 
swallowed a great big animal 
