<DOCNO> AP901218-0246 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the board that makes the nations accounting 
rules has approved a farreaching change in the way businesses 
report healthcare costs for retired workers a move spurring 
companies to reduce retiree benefits 
the new rule which takes effect in 1993 requires companies to 
subtract from their annual earnings a portion of the costs of the 
benefits they have promised to future retirees 
experts say a handful of large companies already have instituted 
cutbacks in retiree health benefits to reduce the rule changes 
financial impact on their earnings statements 
the financial accounting standards board a federally sanctioned 
body that sets the standards for how companies report their 
financial condition approved the change dec 7 said fasb project 
manager diana scott the board gave preliminary approval to the new 
rule in october 
scott said detailed copies of the rule change will be made 
publicly available beginning friday 
theres going to be a lot of costcutting in the next 23 
years said dale yamamoto a group actuary with towers perrin a 
benefits consulting firm 
previously businesses reported only the current years outlays 
for retiree benefits in what was commonly called a pay as you 
go basis 
but the accounting profession argued that this gave investors 
and other company stakeholders an inaccurate picture of a companys 
financial health by understating what their longrange obligations 
actually were 
the new rule does not require companies to set aside money for 
future retirees but it has the potential to slash billions of 
dollars from companies financial earnings in the short term 
hurting their appeal to investors experts say 
at the same time it may help their longterm performance by 
forcing them to prepare for a fiscal future darkened by the rising 
cost of health care 
health care costs have been increasing at annual rates of about 
14 percent for many large companies consultants say far exceeding 
the nations inflation rate for companies with particularly large 
numbers of retirees such as automakers and steelmakers for 
example the benefit obligations are enormous 
for many future retirees the rulechange is generally not good 
news benefits consultants say that companies that have already 
moved to reduce their health care costs include trw american 
airlines american telephone amp telegraph and pillsbury 
while businesses do not have to start subtracting projected 
retiree benefits until their 1993 financial statements many 
already have taken measures because the magnitude of the 
obligation has gotten a lot of companies to focus on what they have 
promised and to amend that said fasbs scott 
the options that companies have instituted or are considering 
include having future retirees share the cost of paying for health 
benefits requiring them to use costcontaining health management 
organizations and relating the contributions retirees kick in to 
their number of years with the company 
in the latter instance workers who have worked more years would 
pay less 
another more drastic costsaving measure companies are 
exploring is capping the total amount paid per year in medical 
benefits to each retiree 
other companies may simply choose to report a significant 
liability on their balance sheets but that option is not expected 
to be widely used 
some companies are very sensitive to reported earnings said 
jeffrey gathers a towers perrin consultant 
under the new rule companies have the option of reporting their 
entire financial obligation to future retirees on the annual 
financial statement or to amortize or spread out that expected 
obligation over the next 20 years said richard j poccia a 
partner at coopers amp lybrand one of the leading us accounting 
firms 
its hard to say which way companies will go he said 
some companies could have the view its worth getting behind 
them 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

