banking industry 
but some analysts predicted tuesday that further action looms to 
nurse ailing banks and the economy as a whole back to health 
citicorp said it would lay off 8000 workers planned to slash 
its annual dividend 78 cents to 1 per share and set aside 350 
million to cover bad commercial loans the shakeup is estimated to 
provide citicorp 800 million in annual savings 
the layoffs are planned over the next three years citicorp 
said 
later in the day the federal reserve wielded its most powerful 
tool to stimulate economic growth by cutting the discount rate the 
interest it charges to make loans to banks by percent to 6 
percent 
stocks and bonds rallied on the fed announcement with the dow 
jones industrial average rising 3341 points to 262673 
citicorps stock rose 75 cents a share in heavy trading 
it was the discount rates first drop since august 1986 and 
appeared to be part of a larger plan by the fed to loosen credit to 
stimulate economic growth 
they are obviously separate reactions to a similar problem 
said jim chessen of the american bankers association in washington 
falling real estate values and a widening national recession 
have led to problems in the banking industry not seen since the 
great depression of the 1930s many banks have closed others are 
cutting operations and the federal insurance fund protecting 
depositor accounts is running out of money 
chessen the abas deputy director for policy development said 
the moves are a response to slackening demand for loans and 
problems with credit quality in parts of the country particularly 
recessionstruck new england and the southwest 
the economic downturn has been blamed on the failure of 734 
banks nationwide in the last 3 years which has drained the 
governments deposit insurance fund on monday federal deposit 
insurance corp chairman william seidman discussed proposals to 
revive the fund with 24 billion from a 1 percent assessment on all 
bank deposits 
